Essex, England":"Belchamp Walter, Essex, England","England":"England","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, England"},"nl":{"about 1514–":"circa 1514–Overleden","1518–Female":"1518–Overleden","1544–Male":"1544–Overleden","1555–1612":"1555–1612","1560–Male":"1560–Overleden","1562–Female":"1562–Overleden","1514–Male":"1514–Overleden","1 April 1560":"1 april 1560","26 October 1539":"26 oktober 1539","1560":"1560","1558":"1558","1514":"1514","1612":"1612","1555":"1555","1544":"1544","about 1514":"circa 1514","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","1562":"1562","about 1544":"circa 1544","before 25 October 1562":"vóór 25 oktober 1562","1518":"1518","1549":"1549","Belchamp St Paul, Essex, England":"Belchamp St Paul, Essex, England","Belchamp Walter, Essex, England":"Belchamp Walter, Essex, England","England":"England","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, England"},"en":{"about 1514–":"about 1514–Deceased","1518–Female":"1518–Deceased","1544–Male":"1544–Deceased","1555–1612":"1555–1612","1560–Male":"1560–Deceased","1562–Female":"1562–Deceased","1514–Male":"1514–Deceased","1 April 1560":"1 April 1560","26 October 1539":"26 October 1539","1560":"1560","1558":"1558","1514":"1514","1612":"1612","1555":"1555","1544":"1544","about 1514":"about 1514","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","1562":"1562","about 1544":"about 1544","before 25 October 1562":"before 25 October 1562","1518":"1518","1549":"1549","Belchamp St Paul, Essex, England":"Belchamp St Paul, Essex, England","Belchamp Walter, Essex, England":"Belchamp Walter, Essex, England","England":"England","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Underwood","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived below a wood on a hillside, from Middle English <i>under</i> + <i>wude</i>, <i>wode</i> ‘wood’, or a habitational name for someone from any place so named.","History: Joseph Underwood emigrated from England to Watertown, MA, in 1637. William Underwood came from England to Concord, MA, before 1640, later settling in Chelmsford, MA. In VA, the name was established by Thomas William Underwood, who came from Norfolk, England, in 1675."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":35,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":44,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705207,"age":71,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705208,"age":73,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705212,"age":106,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Underwood of Belchamp,Essex was born about 1514, in England. He married Agnes Martin of Belchamp, Essex on 26 October 1539, in Belchamp St Paul, Essex, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1514–":"umbes 1514–Surnud","1518–Female":"1518–Surnud","1544–Male":"1544–Surnud","1555–1612":"1555–1612","1560–Male":"1560–Surnud","1562–Female":"1562–Surnud","1514–Male":"1514–Surnud","1 April 1560":"1. aprill 1560","26 October 1539":"26. oktoober 1539","1560":"1560","1558":"1558","1514":"1514","1612":"1612","1555":"1555","1544":"1544","about 1514":"umbes 1514","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","1562":"1562","about 1544":"umbes 1544","before 25 October 1562":"enne 25. oktoobrit 1562","1518":"1518","1549":"1549","Belchamp St Paul, Essex, England":"Belchamp St Paul, Essex, England","Belchamp Walter, Essex, England":"Belchamp Walter, Essex, England","England":"England","Dorchester, Dorset, England":"Dorchester, Dorset, England"},"fi":{"about 1514–":"noin 1514–Kuollut","1518–Female":"1518–Kuollut","1544–Male":"1544–Kuollut","1555–1612":"1555–1612","1560–Male":"1560–Kuollut","1562–Female":"1562–Kuollut","1514–Male":"1514–Kuollut","1 April 1560":"1. huhtikuuta 1560","26 October 1539":"26. lokakuuta 1539","1560":"1560","1558":"1558","1514":"1514","1612":"1612","1555":"1555","1544":"1544","about 1514":"noin 1514","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","1562":"1562","about 1544":"noin 1544","before 25 October 1562":"ennen vuotta 25. lokakuuta 1562","1518":"1518","1549":"1549","Belchamp St Paul, Essex, England":"Belchamp St Paul, Essex, England","Belchamp Walter, Essex, England":"Belchamp Walter, Esse